Task 3: Explore Docker Terminologies and Components

Key Docker Terminologies
Image: A read-only template used to create containers. It includes the OS, application code, and dependencies.

Container: A runtime instance of an image. It is an isolated process that runs the application.

Dockerfile: A text file containing the instructions needed to build a Docker image.

Volume: A persistent storage mechanism that lives outside the container, ensuring data is not lost when a container is deleted.

Network: A communication layer that allows containers to talk to each other or the outside world.


Main Docker Components
Docker Engine: The client-server application that builds and runs containers. 
It includes the Docker Daemon (which manages objects) and the REST API.

Docker Hub: A public registry (like GitHub but for images) where you can push, pull, and store your container images.

Docker Desktop/CLI: The interface used by the user to send commands (like docker build or docker run) to the Docker Engine.


Interaction:
The user uses the CLI to send a command to the Docker Engine.
The Engine then checks locally for the required Image. 
If not found, it pulls it from Docker Hub, then creates and runs the Container.
  
